05373nam a22007215i 9780813539270DE-B159720220524034747.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220524t20062006nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97808135392707 a10.36019/97808135392702doi  a(DE-B1597)530240  a(OCoLC)71842945  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 7aSOC0000002bisacsh1 aLeibing, Annette, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aThinking About Dementia :bCulture, Loss, and the Anthropology of Senility /cLawrence Cohen, Annette Leibing. 1aNew Brunswick, NJ : bRutgers University Press, c[2006] 4c©2006  a1 online resource (320 p.) :b1  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudies in Medical Anthropology0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aBringing together essays by nineteen respected scholars, this volume approaches dementia from a variety of angles, exploring its historical, psychological, and philosophical implications. The authors employ a cross-cultural perspective that is based on ethnographic fieldwork and focuses on questions of age, mind, voice, self, loss, temporality, memory, and affect. Taken together, the essays make four important and interrelated contributions to our understanding of the mental status of the elderly. First, cross-cultural data show that the aging process, while biologically influenced, is also culturally constructed. Second, ethnographic reports raise questions about the diagnostic criteria used for defining the elderly as demented. Third, case studies show how a diagnosis affects a patient's treatment in both clinical and familial settings. Finally, the collection highlights the gap that separates current biological understandings of aging from its cultural meanings. As Alzheimer's disease and other forms of dementia continue to command an ever-increasing amount of attention in medicine and psychology, this book will be essential reading for anthropologists, social scientists, and health care professionals.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aBallenger, Jesse F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBasting, Anne Davis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChatterji, Roma, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCohen, Lawrence, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aCohen, Lawrence, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFlores, Yvette, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFranz, Carol, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGraham, Janice E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHernandez, Isabel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHinton, Ladson, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKaufman, Sharon R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKontos, Pia C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLeibing, Annette, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLloyd, Stephanie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLock, Margaret, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMclean, Athena Helen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMitteness, Linda S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPrest, Janalyn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/voc